''Dragon Quest II'' was ported to [[MSX]] computers in February 1988,<ref>{{cite web|title=ドラゴンクエストII 悪霊の神々 (MSX1版)|url=http://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=23570|publisher=Enterbrain|access-date=22 June 2013|language=ja}}</ref> but the ported version had many issues like choppy scrolling, black-surround characters titles, poor graphics, along with sluggish combat and menus.<ref name="Kalata" /> The MSX2-ported version was released in May 1988 in Japan.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=23571 | title=ドラゴンクエストII 悪霊の神々 (MSX2版) | publisher=Enterbrain | language=ja}}</ref>

On December 18, 1993,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jp.square-enix.com/archive/dq1-2_sfc/|title=ドラゴンクエスト I・II|publisher=Square Enix|access-date=2012-03-24|language=ja}}</ref> ''Dragon Quest II'' was [[Enhanced remake|remade]] and combined with ''[[Dragon Quest]]'' as part of ''Dragon Quest I & II'' for the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super Famicom]], which used ''Dragon Quest V''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s engine.<ref name="Kalata" /> Besides enhanced in graphics and sound, gameplay was also improved. The Super Famicom remake features an improved enemy targeting system: if an enemy is defeated before a character who was assigned to attack can perform its attack move, the character will attack another enemy rather than do nothing like in the Famicom version. And like its successors, players can find stat-improving items from pots or dressers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dragon Quest I+II|url=http://www.dqshrine.com/dq/dq1-2/|publisher=dqshrine.com|access-date=18 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022174320/http://www.dqshrine.com/dq/dq1-2/|archive-date=2012-10-22}}</ref> The Super Famicom remake was only released in Japan.<ref name="Kalata" />

In 1999, ''Dragon Quest I & II'' was released for [[Game Boy Color]]; the game is also compatible with the [[Game Boy]].<ref name="IGN" /> A year later, it was [[Internationalization and localization|localized]] in America as ''Dragon Warrior I & II''.<ref name="Kalata" /> This remake is similar to the Super Famicom version, but with 8-bit graphics. Compared with the NES version, it featured better graphics and was less difficult.  The remake also provided a quick-save function to allow players save and load game anywhere unless they reset the Game Boy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dragon Warrior I+II|url=http://www.dqshrine.com/dw/dw1-2gb/|publisher=dqshrine.com|access-date=18 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019223126/http://www.dqshrine.com/dw/dw1-2gb/|archive-date=2012-10-19}}</ref> In the Game Boy Color localization, the main characters' and towns' names were retranslated to be similar to the original Japanese names:<ref name="Kalata" /> legendary hero "Erdrick" was retranslated as "Loto", and the castle name "Midenhall" was re-dubbed "Lorasia". The original translation had a lot of errors, and Enix changed the names to help fix that.<ref name="gamespot" />

''Dragon Quest II'' was remade for Japanese [[NTT DoCoMo]] brand cell phones in 2005.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.itmedia.co.jp/mobile/articles/0910/02/news089.html | title=ふぉーんなハナシ：携帯版「ドラクエIII」に採用された"新要素" | author=田中聡 | publisher=ITmedia | date =2009-10-02 | language=ja | access-date=2013-06-21}}</ref> The remakes size was four times bigger than the original ''Dragon Quest'' port,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.itmedia.co.jp/mobile/articles/0505/17/news047.html | title= FOMA向け「ドラゴンクエストII」完全移植版を制作| publisher=ITmedia | date =2005-05-17 | language=ja | access-date=2013-06-21}}</ref> and since phone capacity was limited, the game was divided into two parts. The first part was pre-installed in cell phones and the second part could be downloaded for free. The world map was provided by a pre-installed PDF file.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.itmedia.co.jp/mobile/articles/0505/17/news029.html | title=フルブラウザ＋2.5インチ液晶＋ドラクエII──「N901iS」| author=斎藤健二 | publisher=ITmedia | date =2005-05-17 | language=ja | access-date=2013-06-21}}</ref> In 2006 Japanese mobile companies [[Binary Runtime Environment for Wireless|BREW]] and [[SoftBank]] also started selling the game on their mobile platforms.<ref>{{cite web|title=BREW対応「ドラゴンクエストII 悪霊の神々」を配信開始|url=http://www.itmedia.co.jp/mobile/articles/0601/20/news009.html|publisher=ITmedia|access-date=22 June 2013|language=ja|date=2006-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=ドラクエ2やFF2など、ソフトバンク端末向けアプリ投入──スクウェア・エニックス|url=http://www.itmedia.co.jp/mobile/articles/0609/19/news107.html|publisher=ITmedia|access-date=22 June 2013|language=ja|date=2006-09-19}}</ref>

Both the Famicom and Super Famicom versions of this game, along with ''Dragon Quest'' and ''Dragon Quest III'', were re-released under the ''Dragon Quest 25th Anniversary Collection'' compilation for the [[Wii]] in Japan on September 15, 2011.<ref name="Collection">{{cite web|title=Dragon Quest Collection to Come With Bonus Dragon Quest X Video|url=http://www.rpgamer.com/news/Q2-2011/063011b.html|author=Cassandra Ramos|publisher=RPGamer|access-date=21 June 2013|date=2011-06-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704015606/http://www.rpgamer.com/news/Q2-2011/063011b.html|archive-date=4 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Wii compilation featured interruptive save functions for each games.<ref>{{cite web|title=FC版のI・IIには「ふっかつのじゅもん」も。Wii「ドラゴンクエスト25周年記念 ファミコン＆スーパーファミコン ドラゴンクエストI・II・III」の最新情報が到着|url=http://www.4gamer.net/games/132/G013271/20110518072/|publisher=4gamer.net|access-date=21 June 2013|author=Gueed|language=ja|date=2011-05-26}}</ref> The compilation also included original copies of the strategy guides for the games, along with original artwork and material on the games' development.<ref name="Collection" />

Square Enix announced the first eight ''Dragon Quest'' titles would be re-released on [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]] in Japan.<ref name="dq1-8-mobile">{{cite web|url=http://www.jp.square-enix.com/company/ja/news/2013/html/56a7abe635cc1de7c0719e76f250d640.html|title=「ドラゴンクエストVIII」の世界がスマートフォンで展開！ 「ドラゴンクエスト」シリーズ スマートフォンに続々登場！|publisher=[[Square Enix]]|date=2013-10-08|access-date=2013-10-08|language=ja}}</ref> This ''Dragon Quest II'' was based on the previous cell phone version while optimized for smartphones and was released on June 26, 2014, in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itmedia.co.jp/mobile/articles/1406/19/news104.html |title=スマホ向け「ドラゴンクエストII」が6月26日に配信開始 |publisher= ITmedia Mobile}}</ref> An English version was released on October 9, 2014, under the title ''Dragon Quest II: Luminaries of the Legendary Line''.<ref>{{cite web|date=2014-10-09|access-date=2016-02-07|author=Square Enix Members|title=DRAGON QUEST II: Luminaries of the Legendary Line is now available on iOS and Android|url=http://na.square-enix.com/us/blog/dragon-quest-ii-luminaries-legendary-line-now-available-ios-and-android}}</ref> Square Enix registered this trademark in Japan in 2013, and in United States in early 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2013/11/20/dragon-quest-fans-heres-glimmer-hope-localized-games/ |title=Dragon Quest Fans, Here's A Glimmer Of Hope For Localized Games |author=Spencer|date=2013-11-20|access-date=2016-02-07|publisher=Siliconera}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2014/02/10/dragon-quest-games-drawing-near-luminaries-legendary-line-trademark-registered-usa/ |title=Dragon Quest Games Drawing Near? Luminaries Of The Legendary Line Registered In The USA |author=Spencer|date=2014-02-10|access-date=2016-02-07|publisher=Siliconera}}</ref>

In the [[Nintendo Direct]] in June 2024, a HD-2D remake of ''Dragon Quest'' and ''II'' was announced to be released in 2025 for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Nintendo Switch]], [[PlayStation 5]] and [[Xbox Series X/S]].<ref name="dqi-&-II-HD-2D-RE"/>

