=== Sales ===
''Dragon Quest II'' received both critical and financial success in Japan.  The Famicom version sold 500,000 copies on its first release in Japan,<ref>{{cite journal |title=Digest of Japanese Industry & Technology: DJIT. |journal=Digest of Japanese Industry & Technology (DJIT) |date=1993 |issue=276–282 |page=35 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Jj9UAAAAMAAJ |publisher=Japan Trade & Industry Publicity |quote="Dragon Quest II," released in the following year of 1987, sold 500,000 copies on the first release, and 2,200,000 copies in total.}}</ref> and {{nowrap|2.4 million}} copies by the end of the year,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fujii|first=Daiji|date=2005-06-10|title=The Birth of "Final Fantasy": Square Corporation|url=http://ousar.lib.okayama-u.ac.jp/40488|journal=岡山大学経済学会雑誌 (Okayama Economic Review)|publisher=[[Okayama University]]|volume=37|issue=1|pages=63–88 (67–71)|issn=0386-3069|via=Okayama University Scientific Achievement Repository}}</ref><ref name="shipment">{{cite web|date=2004-02-09|title=February 2, 2004 - February 4, 2004|url=http://www.square-enix.com/jp/ir/e/explanatory/download/0404-200402090000-01.pdf#page=27|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060506015857/http://www.square-enix.com/jp/ir/e/explanatory/download/0404-200402090000-01.pdf|archive-date=2006-05-06|access-date=2008-12-15|publisher=[[Square Enix]]|page=27}}</ref> grossing several hundred million dollars.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fujii|first=Daiji|date=2005-06-10|title=The Birth of "Final Fantasy": Square Corporation|url=http://ousar.lib.okayama-u.ac.jp/40488|journal=岡山大学経済学会雑誌 (Okayama Economic Review)|publisher=[[Okayama University]]|volume=37|issue=1|pages=63–88 (82)|issn=0386-3069|via=Okayama University Scientific Achievement Repository}}</ref> The Famicom version's total sales had later increased to {{nowrap|2.41 million}} as of 2008.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ja:日々是遊戯：歴代「ドラクエ」シリーズでもっとも売れたタイトルは!?|url=http://www.itmedia.co.jp/games/articles/0906/18/news082.html|publisher=ITmedia|access-date=16 July 2013|language=ja|date=2009-06-18}}</ref> The Super Famicom and Game Boy Color remakes together shipped in excess of 1.92 million copies worldwide.<ref name="shipment" /> The Japan Mobile version was downloaded more than one million times.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.4gamer.net/games/036/G003681/20101102006/ | title= 携帯アプリ「DQIII そして伝説へ・・・」100万DL達成記念にデコメ配信 | publisher= 4Gamer.net | date= November 2, 2010| access-date=July 22, 2013 | language= ja}}</ref> The game was included in a 2011 compilation called ''Dragon Quest Collection'' for the [[Wii]], which sold 403,953 copies.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://andriasang.com/comznq/game_sales_4gamer/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120123140412/http://andriasang.com/comznq/game_sales_4gamer/|archive-date=January 23, 2012| title=2011 Game Sales Chart and Sales Trends | publisher=andriasang.com| author=Anoop Gantayat| date=January 16, 2012 | access-date=April 4, 2013}}</ref>

=== Reviews ===
Readers of ''{{ill|Family Computer Magazine|ja|ファミリーコンピュータMagazine|vertical-align=sup}}'' gave it a score of 28.02 out of 30,<ref name="famimaga114">{{Cite magazine | script-title = ja:5月10日号特別付録 ファミコンロムカセット オールカタログ |date = 1991-05-10 |publisher = [[Tokuma Shoten]] |magazine = [[:ja:Family Computer Magazine|Family Computer Magazine]] |volume = 7 |number = 9 |pages = 114–115 }}</ref> and named it the best overall cartridge game of the year.<ref name="famimaga379">{{Cite magazine | script-title = ja:5月10日号特別付録 ファミコンロムカセット オールカタログ |date = 1991-05-10 |publisher = [[Tokuma Shoten]] |magazine = [[:ja:Family Computer Magazine|Family Computer Magazine]] |volume = 7 |number = 9 |page = 379}}</ref> In 2006, readers of ''[[Famitsu]]'' magazine voted the game the 17th best video game of all time.<ref name="fam900" /><ref>{{cite web | author=Campbell, Colin | date=March 3, 2006 | title=Japan Votes on All Time Top 100 | url=http://www.next-gen.biz/features/japan-votes-all-time-top-100 | work=Edge-Online.com | access-date=2007-12-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120110224117/http://www.next-gen.biz/features/japan-votes-all-time-top-100|archive-date=2012-01-10}}</ref>

The game is generally known for fixing problems found in the first game, including improvements such as allowing parties of three characters, having a larger world, better graphics, and the ability to carry more items.<ref name="gamespot">{{cite web | author=Provo, Frank | date=September 24, 2000 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206211834/http://www.gamespot.com/dragon-warrior-i-and-ii/reviews/dragon-warrior-iandii-review-2635235/|archive-date=2013-02-06 |title=Dragon Warrior I&II review | url=http://www.gamespot.com/gbc/rpg/dragonwarrior1_2/review.html?tag=mncol;txt| work=Gamespot.com | access-date=2009-09-23}}</ref><ref name="famimaga114" /> Other noted improvements were keys that can be used multiple times and new strategic elements introduced because of larger parties and larger groups of enemies.<ref name="gamespot" /> The game's music is often praised, despite its limited 8-bit capabilities.<ref name="gamespot" /> Considered a classic for the RPG genre, the game is regarded as praiseworthy.<ref>{{cite web | author=Wheeler, Commodore | date=September 21, 2000 | title=Dragon Warrior I&II | url=http://www.rpgfan.com/reviews/dragonwarrior1%262/Dragon_Warrior_1%262.html | work=RPGfan.com | access-date=2009-09-23 | archive-date=2019-06-03 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190603051925/http://www.rpgfan.com/reviews/dragonwarrior1%262/Dragon_Warrior_1%262.html | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author=Nix, Mark | date=October 4, 2000 | title=Dragon Warrior I&II | url=http://gameboy.ign.com/articles/164/164493p1.html| work=IGN.com | access-date=2009-09-23}}</ref> Japanese reviews highlighted the Famicom version's difficulty, stemming from issues such as the many traps in the Cave of Rhone, and the final boss's ability to cast a "Healall" spell, and this has led to some critics calling the game "the most difficult ''Dragon Quest''".<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=オトナファ|date=2009-02-20|title=Enterbrain Review|page=53|publisher=Enterbrain|location=Japan|language=ja}}</ref> After ''Dragon Quest III'' was released, director Koichi Nakamura said "In result, ''Dragon Quest II'' received favourable reviews from everybody, but as myself on the creator's side, I feel that I did about only half what I wanted to do."<ref>{{cite book | title = 虹色ディップスイッチ | publisher = [[ASCII (company)|アスキー]] | chapter = 中村光一×堀井雄二「『ドラクエIII』の楽しみどころ」 | year = 1990 | url = http://dragonquestage.blog.fc2.com/blog-entry-84.html}}</ref>

Remakes of ''Dragon Quest II'' were also successful and well received. ''Famitsu'' awarded the Japanese Super Famicom remake a 35/40.<ref name="FamiSFC" /> The Game Boy Color remake got a 30/40 from ''Famitsu'',<ref name="FamiGBC" /> and the U.S. version, ''Dragon Warrior I & II'', received fairly high marks, including an 8.0 out of 10 from [[IGN]],<ref name="IGN" /> a 9.6 out of 10 from [[GameSpot]],<ref name="gamespot" /> and 8 out of 10 from ''[[Nintendo Power]]''.<ref name="NpGBC" /> It also received the RPGamer's Game Boy Color Award of the Year for 2000.<ref name="RPGamer2000" />

=== Other media ===
The release of ''Dragon Quest II'' also promoted sales of the original ''Dragon Quest'',<ref name="Nakamura" /> and with the success of ''Dragon Quest II'', the series became a Japanese cultural phenomenon.<ref name="fam900">{{cite magazine|script-title=ja:読者が選ぶ心のベストゲーム100|magazine=Famitsu|publisher=Enterbrain|issue=900|date=2006-03-03|language=ja}}</ref> The sequel to ''Dragon Quest II'', ''[[Dragon Quest III|Dragon Quest III: The Seeds of Salvation]]'', was released in 1988 in Japan.<ref name="famidq123" /> It serves as a prequel to the first two games and follows the ancestor of the main characters, the legendary hero [[Erdrick]];<ref name="nathan">{{cite web|title=Remembering Our Dragon Quests|url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/feature/26419|publisher=Nintendo World Report, LLC.|access-date=22 June 2013|author=Nathan Mustafa|date=2011-05-27}}</ref> the three games are collectively called "Erdrick Saga Trilogy".<ref name="famidq123">{{cite web|title="ロトの伝説三部作"がWiiに！ 『ドラゴンクエスト25周年記念 ファミコン＆スーパーファミコン ドラゴンクエストI・II・III』|url=http://www.famitsu.com/news/201105/26043927.html|publisher=[[Enterbrain]]|access-date=21 June 2013|language=ja|date=2011-05-26}}</ref> Also with the success of the Game Boy Color remake, Enix released a Game Boy Color ''[[Dragon Quest III#Remakes|Dragon Warrior III]]'' in 2001, which was based on the Japan-only Super Famicom update of the original ''Dragon Quest III''.<ref>{{cite web| author=Dustin Hubbard and Dwaine Bullock | year=2001 | title=Dragon Warrior III at DQ Shrine| url=http://www.dqshrine.com/dw/dw3gb/| access-date=April 10, 2008}}</ref> The world of ''Dragon Quest II'' was later used as the setting of ''[[Dragon Quest Monsters: Caravan Heart]]'' on the [[Game Boy Advance]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rpgamer.com/games/dq/dqm3/reviews/dqm3strev1.html | title=Dragon Quest Monsters: Caravan Heart - Staff Retroview | author=Michael Baker | publisher=PRGamer | access-date=2013-06-21 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613161533/http://www.rpgamer.com/games/dq/dqm3/reviews/dqm3strev1.html | archive-date=2013-06-13 | url-status=dead }}</ref>

